For completeness sake, a snippet like the following triggered the error:
```typescript
import mongoose from 'mongoose';
import mongoosePaginate from 'mongoose-paginate-v2';
```

title: [jscodeshift] Add types for jscodeshift 0.6
body:
[Jscodeshift](https://github.com/facebook/jscodeshift/) is a very popular tool for writing codemods (ast-based transforms of code). 

Here is an example of a jscodeshift transform (taken from the default contents of the transform panel on [AST Explorer](https://astexplorer.net/)). This code reverses the names of all identifiers (indeed useless, but certainly fun ).

```
function transform(file, { j }) {
  return j(file.source)
    .find(j.Identifier)
    .forEach(path => {
      j(path).replaceWith(
        j.identifier(path.node.name.split('').reverse().join(''))
      );
    })
    .toSource();
}
```

Even in this simple example, we can start to see why TypeScript would be beneficial.
`j.Identifier` is a kind of node and there are [hundreds of node kinds](https://github.com/benjamn/ast-types/blob/master/gen/nodes.ts).
`j.identifier(...)` is a node builder and there are [hundreds of those too](https://github.com/benjamn/ast-types/blob/master/gen/builders.ts) with many function arguments.
The autocomplete and type-checking benefits for nodes and builders, as well as for the jscodeshift api in general has made me much more productive when writing codemods (with a local copy of this d.ts file). And had this been around when I got started with jscodeshift, it would have made it more approachable and easier to learn.

Here is a demonstration of TypeScript in action with the above example.

![jscodeshift-ts](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/723547/48811967-02984680-ece5-11e8-8821-4c33c0646288.gif)

Jscodeshift depends on recast and ast-types and they make up a significant part of its API. I worked with @benjamn to convert the [recast](https://github.com/benjamn/recast/pull/554) and [ast-types](https://github.com/benjamn/ast-types/pull/300) repos to TypeScript. This PR uses those type annotations and adds types for jscodeshift. This PR the final step to a TypeScript-powered developer experience for writing jscodeshift codemods.

title: fix: [node] ParsedUrlQuery -- handle undefined parameters
body:
Since we can never truly guarantee that a query string will contain a given parameter, we need to handle that case by being explicit that any particular query string parameter may return `undefined` (i.e., that parameter wasn't provided). Right now, the signature says `string | string[]`, which is incorrect.

As an example to consider:
```
const fn = (arg: string | string[]) => console.log(arg)
const {query: {p}} = url.parse('http://example.com/?q=a&q=b&r=c', true)
fn(p) // should be a compiler error
```

In this case, `p` will _definitely_ be `undefined`, but the TypeScript compiler will wrongly think that it's either `string | string[]`, and thus `fn` will accept an `undefined` where it shouldn't.

body:
## Changing an existing definition ([Docs](https://stellar.github.io/js-stellar-sdk/), Source: [SDK](https://github.com/stellar/js-stellar-sdk) & [BASE](https://github.com/stellar/js-stellar-sdk))

Among other things mentioned below, this PR also standardizes the way how types are grouped together. That applies to: AssetType, AuthFlag, MemoType, Operation, OperationOptions, OperationType, Signer, SignerOptions. Now, all of them should feel similar to enums (the only real enum is `Networks`). Here's example for Operation:

```ts
import { Operation } from 'stellar-sdk'  // Or 'stellar-base', either works now.
let anyOp: Operation;
let paymentOp: Operation.Payment;
console.log(Operation.Payment)  // Error -> not a run-time value.
```


Changes:

- fix(operations): default to widest type
- fix: add default type argument everywhere
- refactor: plain responses in Horizon namespace
- feat: PriceR, Flags, Account{Signer,Thresholds}
- fix: TransactionRecord
- feat: parameterize Transaction
- feat: extract module `stellar-base`
- fix: change fake enums into type+namespace
- feat: TransactionOperation -> Operation
- refactor: simplify SignerUnion
- feat: don't export utility types
- fix: Memo.text can be either string or Buffer


Breaking Changes:

- several `Server.*` -> `Horizon.*`
- There's two distinct `Server.*Record` & `Horizon.*Response`, choose wisely
- `ASSET_TYPE` -> `AssetType`
- `Memo*` -> `MemoType.*`
- `Memo.AnyType` -> `MemoType`
- `Memo.AnyValue` -> `MemoValue`
- `Operation.AuthFlags` -> `AuthFlag`
- `Operation.*Options` -> `OperationOptions.*`
- `TransactionOperation` -> `Operation`
- `Operation.Signer*Options` -> `SignerOptions.*`
- `Operation.Signer*` -> `Signer.*`
- `Operation.SignerOptions` -> `SignerOptions`
- `Operation.Signer` -> `Signer`
- `Operation.SignerUnion` is obsolete now


### Work to be done

This is a continued work since #31857. Here are the outstanding problems what I have noticed so far:

- feat: copy over comments from source for intellisense
- feat: separate *Record from plain responses [PARTLY DONE]
    For example, server.submitTransaction() returns plain response instead of enhanced `*Record`s returned by `*CallBuilder`s and thus currently is typed wrong. Furthermore, all `*Record`s are just extending plain responses, and thus obviously separating them would make that clear. Also, it would allow to use plain responses, e.g. for a quick `fetch` call. So far only operations and transaction is migrated.
- feat: introduce AccountId, PublicKey and Secret as types
    That's because at some places is confusing whenever you need an address of existing account, random publicKey or just a string. Comments and intellisense may help a lot:
    ```
    /**
     * 56-character long string, starts with S and passes StrKey.isValidEd25519SecretSeed().
     */
    export type Secret = string;

    /**
     * 56-character long string, starts with G and passes StrKey.isValidEd25519PublicKey().
     * Do not confuse with AccountId.
     */
    export type PublicKey = string;
    /**
     * Like PublicKey, but also points to existing account on the given Network.
     */
    export type AccountId = string;
    ```
